<font color="#FF0000">THE DAY AFTER</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28  0:53:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all - very fine posts!<br><br>
Last week went through 68 essays from a Philadelphia Middle School on &quot;What Memorial Day means to me&quot; by 7th and 8th graders.  While some had an appreciation of the larger issues behind Memorial Day; most connected on a personal level.  A father, an uncle, a grandparent or several were veterans.  It was heartening to find that more than a few took the trouble to explain to the kids what Memorial Day was about.  Was also glad to see that most of the kids got beyond the barbeques and trips down to the beach.<br><br>
Spent Memorial Day Eve in charge of a guard detail from several veterans' organizations protecting our local Vietnam Memorial.  Over the course of the night, a dozen guys came out in the pouring rain and following night chill to see that their would be no disfigurement this year.<br><br>
Out of respect for the two Docs' feelings, I won't go into my invocation &amp; benediction for the day's ceremony, but will just note that those of us who honored the dead of our wars are part of a long human lineage stretching as far back as all human stories.  It's part of being true to who we are.<br>

<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


